with emphasis, "the blinding influence of prejudice."

I had daily conversations with someone of the caravan,
and frequently with several. And although Americans
are slow to change their creed, we had the consolation
to relieve our travelling companions of a heavy load of
prejudice against our holy religion. They parted from us,
exhibiting signs of respect and veneration; nay, even of
preference for Catholicity. These controversies so completely
99 engrossed my mind, my heart and my senses,
that I arrived almost unconsciously on the banks of Snake
