When the American Fur Company began their westward expansion, Drips entered
into their employ, having charge after 1836 of annual expeditions to the mountains.
In 1842, the company having encountered strong opposition, the federal government
was prevailed upon to revive the office of Indian agent. Drips served four
years as agent to the Sioux of the upper Missouri, with an annual salary of $1500.
In this capacity, Drips rendered valuable service to the company. Upon the
expiration of his term of office, he re-entered the company's employment, in which
